<DocsLayout title="Getting Started">
  <h1>Getting Started</h1>

  <p>
    DeployStack is a self-hosted deployment platform with embedded intelligence.
    It runs as two components: <strong>Command</strong> (the central server) and
    <strong>Envoy</strong> (lightweight agents on target machines).
  </p>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Node.js 20+</li>
    <li>npm 10+</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Quick Start</h2>

  <pre><code>{quickStart}</code></pre>

  <p>
    Command starts on <code>http://localhost:3000</code> with demo data seeded
    automatically (3 partitions, 3 environments, 3 operations, and sample
    deployments).
  </p>

  <p>
    For production installation, Docker deployment, environment variable reference,
    and multi-Envoy setup, see the
    <a href="/docs/installation">Installation & Configuration</a> guide.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Concepts</h2>

  <h3>Partitions</h3>
  <p>
    Isolated deployment contexts. Each partition has its own variables, deployment
    history, and configuration. Cross-partition data access is never allowed.
  </p>

  <h3>Operations</h3>
  <p>
    A named deployment workflow with ordered steps. Operations define
    <em>what</em> gets deployed. Steps can be selected from the step type library
    or written as custom commands.
  </p>

  <h3>Environments</h3>
  <p>
    Named deployment targets (production, staging, development) with their own
    variable sets. When variables conflict between partition and environment, the
    conflict policy determines resolution.
  </p>

  <h3>Orders</h3>
  <p>
    Immutable snapshots of a deployment configuration. An order captures the
    exact steps, variables, and config at the time of deployment. Orders can be
    re-executed for reproducible deployments.
  </p>

  <h3>Debrief</h3>
  <p>
    Every agent decision is logged in plain language. The decision log records
    what happened, why, and the context. Failed deployments generate automatic
    postmortem reports.
  </p>

  <h2>API</h2>
  <p>
    Command exposes a RESTful API at <code>/api</code> and an MCP server at
    <code>/mcp</code>. The UI communicates through the REST API.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{apiExamples}</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
